bioghist.head: Historical Note
bioghist.p: According to its corporate charter and bylaws the Chesapeake & Ohio Canal Association continues its mission of protecting, preserving and promoting the assets of the Chesapeake & Ohio Canal Historic Park. The Canal National Historical Park is administered by the National Park Service. Surrounded by more than 20,000 acres of parkland, the canal is 185 miles long and follows the Potomac River. It begins in the Georgetown section of Washington, D.C. and ends in Cumberland, Maryland. Located in Georgetown, the Foundry Mall center is one of five visitors' centers and offers visitors' mule-drawn boat rides along the canal route. Historic sites along the canal include the Harpers Ferry National Historical Park, the Antietam Battlefield, Fort Frederick State Park, and Fort Tonoloway. The Chesapeake & Ohio Canal National Historical Park is open for hiking, biking, camping, canoeing, boating, picnicking, ice skating and rock climbing.

In 1950 as the canal ceased to be commercially useful, plans were made to bulldoze it and pave a super-highway into Maryland's mountains. Supreme Court Justice William O. Douglas was one of the few people who realized the historical, cultural, geological and botanical significance of the Chesapeake & Ohio. He challenged two Washington Post editors to walk the length of the 184-mile Chesapeake & Ohio with him and then decide if it the canal and its structures should be destroyed.

The reporters, along with 32 others, took the eight-day hike in March of 1954 and then joined Douglas in the effort to save the canal. That effort resulted in the formation of the Chesapeake & Ohio Canal Association and, 17 years later, the passage of legislation that created the Chesapeake & Ohio Canal National Historical Park, now one of the major areas of tourism in the National Park System. As one of his last official acts in office in 1961, President Eisenhower proclaimed the canal a national monument. In the mid 1970s the canal and towpath were dedicated to Justice Douplas in honor of his singular contribution to the nation's park system.

The Canal Association was first organized as an advocacy group to preserve the canal. Today, the Association focuses more on recreational and social activities, providing a range of programs and activities encouraging use of the park. The hike that Justice Douglas started in 1954 is now an annual event known as the Heritage hikes, and programs such as the Levels Walkers offer continual detailed reports of the physical status of the park.

Chesapeake & Ohio Canal In 1784, George Washington founded the Potomac Canal Company to begin building a canal along the Potomac River in Virginia. This company was incorporated as the Chesapeake and Ohio Canal Company in 1824. On July 4, 1828, at Little Falls, Maryland, President John Quincy Adams shoveled out the first piece of land that signaled the $11 million dollar construction of the Chesapeake and Ohio Canal. This project would join the canals that existed separately in Virginia and Maryland.

On October 10, 1850, the canal opened, creating a continuous artificial waterway along the Potomac River. However, increased railroad routes quickly diminished the effectiveness of the canal as a major commercial route and by 1925, the Chesapeake & Ohio canal was no longer used commercially. The Baltimore and Ohio Railroad Co. (B&O) then bought the land once owned by the Chesapeake & Ohio Canal Company. In 1938, the B&O Railroad Co. sold the entire canal to the U.S. government for $2 million. The canal was placed under the supervision of the Nationals Park Service in 1950.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This collection contains correspondence, obituaries, reports, photographs, slides, newsletters, booklets, membership data, programs, brochures, minutes, and by-laws. The material dates from the early 1800s to 2022 with the bulk of the material falling between 1954-2013. This material relates to the history of both the Chesapeake and Ohio Canal and the Chesapeake & Ohio Canal Association.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized into six series: Images, Administration files, Audio-visual materials, Personal papers, Records of past presidents Ken Rollins, Rachael Stewart and Carl Linden, and Newsletter: Along the Towpath.

accessrestrict.p: This collection is open for research.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains minutes, memos, correspondence, directories, membership records, articles, reports, awards, maps, and press releases. These materials date from 1828-2010 with the bulk falling from 1954-90. The files include the records of the president's office, Board of Directors, Committees, financial records, legal files, membership data, public relations, programs, history of the association, and reference files.

These files detail the work of this organization including their efforts to preserve the Canal. The presidents whose tenures are included in this collection are Lewis W. Schollenberger (1957-1958), Grant Conway (1959-1961), William E. Davies (1962), Anthony Wayne Smith (1969), Colin Ritter (1970-1971), Carl A. Linden (1972-1974, 1994), Bonnie L. Troxell (1975-1977), Barbara Yeaman (1980), John Chandler (1981-1982) , Bruce W. Wood (1983-1985), Harold A. Larsen (1986-1990), and David M. Johnson (1991-1993).

The Board of Director's files contain information related to the Association's efforts in gaining U.S. Government recognition of the Chesapeake & Ohio canal as an historic park. This group of records also has information about local development and environmental issues. The materials related to the committees demonstrate how the Association continues to promote its mission of protecting, preserving, and promoting the assets of the Chesapeake & Ohio Canal Historic Park. The committees also document the participation of the Association in other local conferences and commissions including the National Historical Park Advisory Commission. The financial records include budgets and treasurer's reports from 1977-94. The legal files include by-laws, and certificates of incorporation and the Davies Legal Fund developed by William Davies to fund the efforts of the Chesapeake & Ohio Canal Association. There are also administrative files related to the Chesapeake & Ohio Canal National Historical Park such as event schedules, organizational charts, environmental assessments, trail development, safety issues, and material related to the Potomac River Greenway Coalition.

The membership files contain information on how the Association recruited, retained, and supported their membership base as well as document biographical information on some of the members. The newsletter, Along the Towpath is also in this series. The public relations and program files has material produced by the Association to advertise the events and activities of the Association. The history files contain persona recollections and interviews from several local citizens who reflect on the lifestyle and community atmosphere that revolve around the canal. Fact sheets and reports contain information on the chronology of events that lead to the Chesapeake & Ohio Canal Association.

Finally, there are reference files with data including articles, brochures, and newsletters from other organizations. One box of reference files in particular contains files documenting the controversy over plans for a Georgetown University boathouse.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains film, audio cassettes, videos, and phonographs. These items date from 1949-95. The phonograph is the 1949 recording of "My Daddy had a Snow-White Mule-Stories of the Chesapeake & Ohio Canal."
